Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place @cream cheese{2%tablespoon} in a #small bowl{} with warm water to soften. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into 1⁄2-inch-thick pieces. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Toss carrots on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of oil, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until tender, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and cook, stirring, until just softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce} and cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in 3⁄4 cup water, @mushroom stock concentrate{1}, half the @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, 1 tsp @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}, and a pinch of salt. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

> For 4 servings, use 1 1⁄2 cups water and 2 tsp Italian Seasoning.

Drain any excess liquid if necessary. Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 5.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with paper towels and season all over with remaining garlic powder, remaining Italian Seasoning, salt, and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

> Swap in pork chops for chicken. Cook pork until browned and cooked through, 4-6 minutes per side.

Transfer to a #cutting board{} and tent with foil to keep warm.

Return pot with couscous to stovetop over low heat. Stir in 1 cup water, @cheese roux concentrate{1%ounce}, cream cheese, and @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}. Cook, stirring, until combined and creamy, ~{30-60%seconds}. Remove from heat.

Slice chicken crosswise.

Divide creamy couscous between shallow #bowls{}; top with chicken and roasted carrots. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.